<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson -- Nov. 22 (10:30am)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>The Families v. O.J. Simpson</H2>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/notebook/">Reporter's Notebook</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/transcripts/">Transcripts</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/">Court TV Reports</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/documents/">Documents and Depositions</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/updates/">Past Updates</A> | 

<A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">Discussion</A>
</FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Simpson Denies Striking, Slapping Or Hitting His Former Wife</B></font><BR>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/casefiles/simpson.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=0 BORDER=0>SANTA MONICA Nov. 22 (10:30 A.M.) -- O.J. Simpson took the stand about 9:20 am in his civil trial here, answering questions about his relationship with Nicole Brown and about domestic violence.</P>

<P>Daniel Petrocelli is conducting the examination, began by asking Simpson when he met Nicole. She was an 18-year-old waitress, Simpson said and he was 29, a pro football player who was married at the time.</P>

<P>"It was a passionate relationship. . . . true?" Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P>"Yes," Simpson said.</P>

<P>Petrocelli: "And it was a problem relationship . . . true?"</P>

<P>Simpson: "Not true."</P>

<P>Petrocelli quickly turned to the 1989 New Years day domestic violence incident, showing pictures of Nicole Brown Simpson's bruised and battered face.</P>

<P>"How many times did you hit Nicole?" Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P>Simpson: "Never."</P>

<P>"How many times did you strike Nicole?"</P>

<P>Simpson: "Never."</P>

<P>Petrocelli: "How many times did you slap Nicole?"</P>
<P>Simpson: "Never."</P>

<P>At one point, Simpson, who described the incident as a "wrassling match" offered to wrassle Petrocelli. Petrocelli agreed, asking Simpson to put him in a headlock, like Simpson did to his wife. Judge Hiroshi Fujisaki refused to allow the demonstration.</P>

<P>Simpson did not lose his cool and the stand, answering questions methodically.</P>
<P>-Robert Schmidt<BR>
<I>Court TV Law Center</i></P>

<P>Find out about <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/coverage.html">Court TV's coverage</A> of the civil trial, and take a look at the <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/promwit.html">witness lists</A> provided by both sides.</P>

