<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson -- Dec. 5 (Noon) </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>The Families v. O.J. Simpson</H2>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/notebook/">Reporter's Notebook</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/transcripts/">Transcripts</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/">Court TV Reports</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/documents/">Documents and Depositions</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/updates/">Past Updates</A> | 

<A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">Discussion</A>
</FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Judge Cautions Jury On Hotline's 'Nicole' Call</B></font><BR>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/casefiles/simpson.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=0 BORDER=0>SANTA MONICA, Dec. 5 (Noon) -- After permitting controversial testimony Wednesday from a domestic violence hotline worker, Judge Hiroshi Fujisaki told jurors Thursday morning in the O.J. Simpson civil trial that the testimony could only be used to show Nicole Brown Simpson's state of mind shortly before she was murdered. The testimony could not be used as evidence that Simpson stalked -- or threatened to kill --- his ex-wife.</P>

<P>Jurors also heard the deposition testimony of Mark Partridge, the attorney who sat next to Simpson on the airplane back to Los Angeles. He testified that Simpson gave him a somewhat detailed account of his ex-wife's death. Simpson, Partridge said, told him his wife and another man were killed in a crime, and the two bodies were found in the garden area at Bundy. Police, however, did not tell Simpson the details of his wife death.</P>

<P>Court recessed at the noon break, as the plaintiffs prepared to rest their case on Friday. Scheduled witnesses are: DNA expert Bruce Weir, Simpson's business lawyer Skip Taft; Goldman's mother Sharon Rufo by videotape; Juditha Brown; and Frederic Goldman.</P>

<P>Judge Fujisaki decided to issue the jury instruction without a request from the lawyers, as he did several days ago when he issued instructions on Simpson's alleged lie detector test. Defense attorney Robert Baker objected to the decision, but was overruled.</P>

<P>The hotline volunteer, Nancy Ney, told jurors on Wednesday that she answered a call from a woman named Nicole, who was being stalked and receiving death threats from her former husband. The caller did not give her last name but said she had been married to a high-profile man for eight years, had two children, and lived in West Los Angeles. Ney also testified that Nicole Brown Simpson's voice on a 911 recording was similar  to the caller's.</P>

<P>The judge told jurors that he admitted the testimony because Nicole Brown Simpson's state of mind has been an issue during the trial. The defense has contended that she was stalking O.J. Simpson and that she acted strangely at the dance recital the night of the murders. The judge also said that it was up to the jury to decide if the caller was really Nicole Brown Simpson. </P>

<P>"The testimony of Nancy Ney . . . was offered . . . to show Nicole's state of mind regarding the relationship at the time the call was made and to explain her conduct as it may relate to Mr. Simpson at the recital the night of her death," Judge Fujisaki said. "The jury must not consider the substance of her statements . . . as evidence of any events or whether such events ever occurred."</P>

<P>The plaintiffs read into the record deposition testimony from two Hertz employees who drove Simpson to and from the airport in Chicago after the murders. James Merrill, who picked Simpson up, said that Simpson, after learning of his ex-wife's death, called him three times within 20 minutes for a ride back to the airport. When Merrill received the first call, he was at home, about a half hour from the airport ,and Simpson's golf bag was in the trunk of his car. He said he suggested that Simpson arrange alternative transportation back to the airport. Simpson testified that Merrill never said that. The plaintiffs contend that Simpson put a small bag containing his bloody clothes into his golf bag and was frantic to get it back.</P>

<P>Merrill also discussed a call Simpson made to him a day after he left Chicago. Simpson testified that he called to apologize for his rudeness. Plaintiffs' attorney Daniel Petrocelli pointed out that Simpson also asked about his golf clubs again and brought up personal information during the conversation. Even though he did not know Merrill, Simpson talked about his deceased ex-wife, his divorce, and his children.</P>

<P>"He told you he loved Nicole, right?" Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P>"Yes," Merrill said.</P>

<P>"And you had never heard of Nicole, right?" Petrocelli continued.</P>

<P>"Yes," Merrill replied.</P>

<P>The Hertz employee who eventually brought Simpson to the airport, Raymond Kilduff, testified that Simpson "wanted to make sure he got his golf clubs back." Kilduff was also asked about the clothes Simpson wore to the airport. He testified that Simpson was wearing a blue jean shirt, blue jean pants, and black loafers without socks. This contradicts Simpson's testimony. He said he left the hotel wearing a white polo shirt and black pants -- the same clothes he wore when he met police later that day at his Rockingham estate. The plaintiffs are suggesting that Simpson bled on his clothes and had to change them before he reached his house. </P>

<P>The attorney Partridge, who sat next to Simpson on the plane, also testified that Simpson was wearing the blue jean outfit.</P>

<P>The plaintiffs briefly read to the jury deposition testimony from Dr. Lenore Walker, a defense expert witness who counseled Simpson after the murders. Walker's testimony was mainly used to verify her notes, which the plaintiffs have been using to impeach some of Simpson's testimony about the 1989 domestic violence incident and about his breakup with Paula Barbieri. Simpson testified that he did not get into a fight with Barbieri about his decision not to bring her to his daughter's dance recital. But Walker's notes tell a different story. One selection read: "Paula out and about and maybe out of town and a little bit upset about not inviting her."</P>
<P>-Robert Schmidt<BR>
<I>Court TV Law Center</i></P>

<P>Find out about <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/coverage.html">Court TV's coverage</A> of the civil trial, and take a look at the <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/promwit.html">witness lists</A> provided by both sides.</P>

