<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson -- Dec. 6 (Noon)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>The Families v. O.J. Simpson</H2>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/notebook/">Reporter's Notebook</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/transcripts/">Transcripts</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/">Court TV Reports</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/documents/">Documents and Depositions</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/updates/">Past Updates</A> | 

<A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">Discussion</A>
</FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Jury To Hear Kardashian's Testimony</B></font><BR>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/casefiles/simpson.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=0 BORDER=0>SANTA MONICA, Dec. 6 (Noon) -- Jurors in the O.J. Simpson civil trial will hear testimony Friday afternoon from Robert Kardashian, Simpson's friend and lawyer, even though he is currently in New York City. Judge Hiroshi Fujisaki ruled at the end of the morning session that the plaintiffs may read into the record excerpts from Kardashian's deposition.</P>

<P>In testimony, Simpson's personal attorney and business manager Leroy "Skip" Taft told the jury that he saw only one cut on Simpson's hand the day after the murders. Taft's testimony contradicted an account he gave in his deposition, when he said he saw at least two cuts on Simpson's finger. Bruce Weir, a statistician specializing in mixed DNA blood samples, also took the stand. He suffered a withering cross-examination by defense lawyer Robert Blasier who confronted him about mistakes he made in his calculations during the criminal trial.</P>

<P>The plaintiffs are likely to read portions of Kardashian's deposition where he talked about Simpson asking him to drive to the airport to pick up his golf clubs. Simpson said that he did not ask Kardashian. The plaintiffs contend that Simpson was frantic about his golf bag because it may have contained bloody clothes or the murder weapon. Also this afternoon, the plaintiffs are scheduled to call relatives of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman: Goldman's parents -- Sharon Rufo (by videotape) and Fredric Goldman -- and Brown's mother, Juditha Brown. When they finish testifying, the plaintiffs are expected to rest their case.</P>

<P>Judge Fujisaki permitted Kardashian's testimony after a short hearing on whether Kardashian was an unavailable witness. The defense argued that because the plaintiffs never served Kardashian with a subpoena, he should not be considered unavailable. At one point, lead defense attorney Robert Baker offered the plaintiffs a deal: "I'll trade you one Kardashian for one Fuhrman."</P>

<P>But Judge Fujisaki did not bite. "Nice try Mr. Baker," he said. "You may read it, I find [Kardashian] unavailable."</P>

<P>Taft's testimony provoked the most hostile examination so far in the civil trial. The business manager told the jury he and Simpson have grown to be close friends over their 27-year relationship, and on the stand Taft was obviously protective of the former football star. The plaintiffs called Taft to testify about one limited area -- the cuts on Simpson's left hand. Simpson testified in the civil trial that he had only one cut on his middle finger when he returned from Chicago on June 13. Two days later Simpson's doctor Robert Huizenga photographed three cuts and seven abrasions on his hands. Simpson told the jury that he received those marks after returning to  Los Angeles, maybe from wrestling with his young son. But Taft, when he was examined for his deposition, said he was "sure" Simpson had two cuts on his left hand on June 13.</P>

<P>The plaintiffs planned to use Taft to contradict Simpson. However when he was questioned by lead plaintiffs attorney Daniel Petrocelli about seeing Simpson's hand on June 13, Taft changed his story.</P>

<P>"You saw some cuts on Mr. Simpson's left hand, correct?" Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P> "As I sit here today I recall seeing one cut, Mr. Petrocelli," Taft replied.</P>

<P> The answer sent Petrocelli into a fury. At several points during his examination Petrocelli borrowed a trick from Simpson's criminal attorney Barry Scheck's infamous examination of LAPD criminalist Dennis Fung, where Scheck ended his  question with a combative: "How about that, Mr. Fung?" Confronting Taft with his deposition, Petrocelli almost shouted, "How about that, Mr. Taft?"</P>

<P>But Taft would not back down from his contention, telling Petrocelli that he was confused about the time period when he gave his deposition. Taft also said that when he met Simpson on the 13th he was "in a major state of shock." On cross-examination, the defense also pointed out that the Los Angeles police, when they identified Simpson on the 13th, found only one cut on his middle finger.</P>

<P>Simpson, who has not been in court since his testimony before Thanksgiving, returned today. He has been attending his child custody case in Orange County, Calif. But it is not in session on Fridays.</P>
<P>-Robert Schmidt<BR>
<I>Court TV Law Center</i></P>

<P>Find out about <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/coverage.html">Court TV's coverage</A> of the civil trial, and take a look at the <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/promwit.html">witness lists</A> provided by both sides.</P>

