<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Court TV Casefiles: O.J. Simpson -- Dec. 9 (Noon)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#DD0000">
<A HREF="/map/top-casefiles.map"><IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/headers/top-casefiles.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A>
<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>The Families v. O.J. Simpson</H2>

<FONT SIZE="-1">
<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/notebook/">Reporter's Notebook</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/transcripts/">Transcripts</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/">Court TV Reports</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/documents/">Documents and Depositions</A> | 

<A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/updates/">Past Updates</A> | 

<A HREF="/discuss/gateway.html">Discussion</A>
</FONT>

<P><FONT SIZE="+1"><B>Goldman Tells Jury About His Son</B></font><BR>
<IMG SRC="/graphics/ctv/casefiles/simpson.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=0 BORDER=0>SANTA MONICA,  Dec. 9 (Noon) -- A choked up Fredric Goldman told jurors about his relationship with his murdered son, Monday morning in the O.J. Simpson civil trial, taking them from Ronald Goldman's childhood as a "happy go lucky kid" through his extensive, but unrealized plans to open a restaurant. </P>

<P>The plaintiffs rested after Goldman's testimony. The defense opened its case with Los Angeles Police Det. Philip Vannatter, who is currently on the stand. Lead defense attorney Robert Baker almost immediately began attacking Vannatter, focusing on the theme that poor police work produced contaminated evidence. Baker accused Vannatter of leaving the evidence-rich Bundy crime scene to investigate O.J. Simpson as a suspect in the murder. Vannatter maintained that he left Bundy and went to Rockingham to notify Simpson of the murder.</P>

<P>After Vannatter, the defense is expected to call LAPD criminalist Andrea Mazzola and LAPD nurse Thano Peratis.</P>

<P>Goldman began his testimony discussing his son's childhood in Illinois. Ron and his father participated in Indian Guides -- a program similar to the Boy Scouts -- and they went on vacations together. Although Ron played Little League, Goldman testified, neither was very interested in sports. They were a close family, and Ron's younger sister Kim used to call him "her second father," Goldman noted.</P>

<P>"Ron had a smile on his face from the day he was born, and he was a happy go lucky kid that never seemed to have a care in the world," Goldman said.</P>

<P>Goldman is suing Simpson for his loss of companionship from Ron's death, and he spent a good part of his testimony detailing the time the they spent together. Because they lived near each other, Goldman testified, he and his son often met for lunch or dinner, ant they attended frequent family events. In the last year of his life, Ron came home for the birthdays of his father, sister, and step-brother, as well as Thanksgiving, Passover, and mother's day, Goldman said. Toward the end of Goldman's testimony, the plaintiffs played a videotape of Ron speaking at his step-sister's Bat Mitzvah in November 1993. The video, which also showed Ron playing air guitar with his father, provoked an outpouring of emotion. Lead plaintiffs attorney Daniel Petrocelli was crying, as were two other Goldman attorneys. One juror appeared to be crying, as well.</P>

<P>"There was something special about our relationship...there was this bond that never dissipated," Goldman said.</P>

<P>Not all of Goldman's testimony painted his son as a saint. During his direct examination, Goldman admitted that Ron was a bit of a "lead foot" and lost his driver's license for amassing so many speeding tickets. Twice Ron was arrested for driving with a suspended license, and he once spent four days in jail because of it. Ron also had money problems and at one point was "in deep," Goldman testified. Ron later filed for bankruptcy because he was $12,000 in debt.</P>

<P>But Ron had moved on after his money problems and had established goals and plans for his life, Goldman testified. Ron planned on opening a restaurant and had asked his father if he would become a partner in the venture. Goldman agreed, he testified, but the plan was never realized. Later when cleaning out Ron's apartment, a tearful Goldman told the jury, he found sample menus and a drawing of the restaurant his son had made.</P>

<P>Each time Goldman mentioned the word "murder," he'd glare at Simpson.</P>

<P>Petrocelli brought Goldman's examination to an emotional close.</P>

<P>"Mr. Goldman, did you love your son?" Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P>"Oh God, yes," Goldman replied.</P>

<P>"Do you miss him?" Petrocelli continued.</P>

<P>"More than you can imagine," Goldman said bursting into tears.</P>

<P>"Do you think of him ever day," Petrocelli asked.</P>

<P>"There isn't a day that goes by when I don't think of Ron," Goldman replied.</P>

<P>After such an emotional examination, Baker conducted a gentle cross-examination. He questioned Goldman briefly about how much time the two spent together, and also inquired about the Goldmans friendships with police and FBI agents who worked on the case. Baker also asked Goldman about the book his family is writing. They received a $450,000 advance, Goldman testified, and the family is keeping about half.</P>

<P>-Robert Schmidt<BR>
<I>Court TV Law Center</i></P>

<P>Find out about <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/coverage.html">Court TV's coverage</A> of the civil trial, and take a look at the <A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/reports/promwit.html">witness lists</A> provided by both sides.</P>

<P><A HREF="/casefiles/simpson/notebook/"><B>Rob Schmidt's Reporter's Notebook</B></A></P>

