<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<H2>Week by Week in the O.J. Simpson Criminal Trial</H2>

<H3>Pre-Trial Developments in the Case (January 11 - 20, 1995)</H3>

<P><B>JANUARY 11</B> - In a devastating attack on O.J. Simpson, the prosecution asserted that the former football legend abused his former wife for 17 years. The revelations came as lawyers began arguments about whether jurors should hear evidence of alleged domestic abuse by Simpson against Nicole Brown Simpson. The prosecution detailed more than 50 alleged incidents of abuse, including a number of alleged beatings and a threat by Simpson to cut off the heads of any of his ex-wife's boyfriends he caught driving his cars. The prosecution argued the evidence established motive and premeditation. The defense countered that the evidence was unsubstantiated and therefore should not be introduced during the trial.</P>

<P>The hearing began after the jurors and alternates were sequestered. Also, Judge Lance Ito ordered a women's shelter that may have served Nicole Brown Simpson to turn over records to the attorneys in the murder trial. The Sojourn shelter in Santa Monica expressed concerns about the cost of complying with the order and about the impact on the privacy of its clients. Judge Ito ruled that a waiver of confidentiality signed by Nicole Brown Simpson's father allowed for the release of the records.</P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 12</B> - The second day of hearings on the admissibility of alleged incidents of domestic abuse opened with the prosecution withdrawing 19 of the 52 incidents that it claims chronicled the alleged pattern of abuse. Still, Deputy District Attorney Lydia Bodin said the remaining incidents were sufficient to prove O.J. Simpson's motive for murder. "When he finally couldn't control her, when she was finally breaking away from him, when she had finally estranged herself from him and tried to distance herself from him, it is the people's contention that he killed her," Bodin said. The state withdrew the items of alleged abuse that were detailed in Nicole Brown Simpson's diary because they were inadmissible hearsay evidence. Judge Lance Ito said he would rule by Tuesday on what evidence would be admitted.</P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 13</B> - A black prosecutor and black defense attorney engaged in a bitter exchange with each accusing the other of bringing up the issue of race in the double murder case. The clash between Deputy District Attorney Christopher Darden and defense attorney Johnnie Cochran Jr. occurred during arguments over whether the defense should be allowed to ask a key detective in the case whether he ever uttered racial slurs against blacks. </P>

<P>The prosecution wants to exclude from trial what it calls "remote, inflammatory and irrelevant character evidence" regarding Det. Mark Fuhrman. The defense has portrayed Fuhrman as a racist with a propensity to lie and plant evidence. It wants to explore allegations that Fuhrman made racially derogatory remarks in the past and tampered with evidence in another case. The defense also has raised the theory that Fuhrman may have planted the bloody glove found on Simpson's estate several hours after the murders of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman.</P>

<P>Meanwhile, a hearing on a motion to quash a prosecution subpoena issued to Simpson's first wife, Marguerite Simpson Thomas, was postponed.</P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 16</B> - Several days before opening arguments in the O.J. Simpson trial on murder charges, a rift has developed between two members of the defense team -- Robert Shapiro and F. Lee Bailey. It also was reported that it's up to defense lawyer Johnnie Cochran to try and resolve the dispute. The feud between Shapiro and Bailey apparently stems from the results of an internal investigation by Simpson's main investigator, William Pavelic, into leaks to the media. According to the New York Times, Pavelic concluded and told Simpson that Bailey was behind a series of leaks aimed at denigrating Shapiro's legal skills and enhancing his role in the case.</P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 17</B> - O.J. Simpson's lawyers sought to prevent the prosecution from using the names of 200 witnesses in their opening arguments at the start of the murder trial. In another development, prosecutors said they no longer needed medical records of the football legend's two children by his first marriage.</P>

<P>In a motion unsealed Tuesday, defense attorney Robert Shapiro complained that the witness lists presented by the prosecution to the defense earlier this year gave Simpson's lawyers no time to check the witness' statements and interview them before opening arguments tentatively set for Thursday. Judge Lance Ito had warned the prosecution at a hearing Jan. 5 that if the defense objected to the late witnesses and showed "good cause" why they should not be mentioned in opening statements, he would rule in their favor.</P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 18</B> - Judge Lance Ito ruled that the jury in the O.J. Simpson case can hear about several instances of domestic abuse in Simpson's marriage to Nicole Brown Simpson including the 1989 incident in which he pleaded no contest to wife beating charges.</P>

<P>The ruling was a major victory for prosecutors, who will try to use the evidence to show that the murder of Nicole Brown Simpson was the culmination of years of abuse.</P>

<P>In his ruling, Ito said that most of the domestic violence evidence can be admitted during the trial because it is necessary to prove motive and intent in the June 12, 1994 slayings of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman.</P>

<P>In earlier rulings, Judge Ito determined that relatives of the victims may sit in the courtroom for most of the trial., He also severely restricted Simpson's jail visitation rights after the sheriff's department complained that a book author met with Simpson in a room reserved for attorneys and material witnesses. </P>

<P>Judge Ito's ruling on the domestic violence issue came a day after prosecutors revealed in court documents that Simpson physically abused his first wife. The allegation was contained in documents filed Jan. 13, in response to a motion by Simpson's first wife Marguerite Thomas to quash a prosecution subpoena calling her to court. She was married to Simpson in 1967. The couple divorced in 1979. The documents also revealed that on the day of his arrest Simpson told his first wife that he was framed for the murders and planned to kill himself. </P>

<P>The court papers included a statement from a police officer who said he responded to a domestic violence radio call at the Simpson home 20 years ago and that Thomas stated then that Simpson had hit her. </P>

<HR WIDTH=375 ALIGN=LEFT>
<P><B>JANUARY 20</B> - Judge Lance Ito ruled that O.J. Simpson's lawyers cannot introduce two claims that detective Mark Fuhrman may be a racist. But Ito left the door open for the defense to use one other alleged racial incident and said he might also allow testimony that Fuhrman used the racial slur "nigger" if the defense could prove it was used "in a relevant incident."</P>

<P>The defense hopes to brand Fuhrman as a racist and to impeach his testimony that he discovered a bloody glove at Simpson's home that matched one found at the scene of the June 12 murders of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ronald Goldman. The defense has hinted that Fuhrman may have planted the glove.</P>

<P>In his ruling, Ito said the defense could not use a 1981 disability lawsuit Fuhrman filed in which he allegedly disparaged blacks and Hispanics. The defense also was barred from using a lawsuit filed against Fuhrman and other officers by a black man who said he was shot by the policeman following a robbery attempt, called "nigger" and had a knife placed near his feet.</P>

<P>In another ruling, Ito said prosecutors could not mention in opening arguments several witnesses who are expected to testify about domestic violence and that they could not appear until the defense team had a chance to interview them.</P>

<HR WIDTH=525 ALIGN=LEFT>
